<http://www.spektrix.com/thecultch/event/137612AJBHTDMJSNVPRQGRKDKRTJPGKVR> a schema:Event;
  schema:name "Michel(le)";
  schema:description """
	<span class=\"BoldText\">Presented by The Cultch<span><br/></span>Produced by Pi Theatre (Vancouver)<span><br/></span><span><br/></span>Written and Performed by: Joey Lespérance<span><br/></span>Directed by: Richard Wolfe</span><span><br/></span><span><br/></span>Historic Theatre 1895 Venables St.<span><br/></span><span><br/></span>From their youngest days as children in suburban Montreal, brothers Joey and Michel found freedom on makeshift backyard stages, performing for family and neighbors in working-class Quebec of the ’60s and ’70s. In a world that offered few spaces for self-expression, these moments of play became a lifeline and a way of expressing who they really were.<span><br/></span><span><br/></span>Joey became a performer in Vancouver, while Michel lit up Montreal’s drag scene before embracing her true identity as Michelle, the woman she had always known herself to be.<span><br/></span><span><br/></span>In his first solo show, inspired by his own life, Joey Lespérance delivers a powerful and deeply personal portrait of identity, resilience, and transformation. Through a story as intimate as it is expansive, Lespérance breathes life into his sibling’s journey, honoring a dream that might otherwise have been lost.<span><br/></span><span><br/></span>With honesty, compassion, striking humanity and undeniable humour, this autobiographical performance celebrates the complexities of family, the weight of societal expectations, and the courage it takes to live authentically.<span><br/></span>
""";
  schema:startDate "2027-03-24T19:30:00"^^xsd:dateTime;
  schema:image <https://system.spektrix.com/thecultch/files/49d24083-e713-4009-a4b3-8e5fabe6d0b1.jpg>;
